  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and regulations aimed at preventing money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) - An international organization that sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime - Provides a framework for international cooperation in preventing money laundering.\n\n3. The Palermo Convention - Requires member states to criminalize money laundering and establish mechanisms to combat it.\n\n4. Basel Committee's Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Principles - Provides guidelines for banks and financial institutions.\n\n5. Various regional agreements and directives, such as the European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives.\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement internal compliance programs\n\nMost countries have their own domestic laws implementing these international standards, with penalties for non-compliance.",
